\section secInstallEcpliseUseMakefiles Build in Eclipse using external Makefiles

In order to build the <strong>UG4</strong> libraries via <em>Eclipse</em>, you 
first must create the Makefiles.
This is done using <em>CMake</em> in the terminal (go 
\ref secInstallUG4CMake "here" if you did not already install <em>CMake</em>).

<ol>
  <li>Open a terminal/shell window</li>
  <li>move into your workspace directory you chose before</li>
  <li><tt>cd ug4</tt></li>
  <li><tt>mkdir build_debug</tt></li>
  <li><tt>cd build_debug</tt></li>
  <li><tt>cmake -DUG_DEBUG=ON ..</tt> --> Makefiles are generated</li>
</ol>

Note, that once the Makefiles have been created, you do not have to rebuild them
at any time.
This step has to be performed only once. 
Now, these Makefiles can be used in <em>Eclipse</em>:

<ol>
  <li>Click right on folder <tt>ug4</tt> -> Choose <em>Properties</em></li>
  <li>Under <em>C/C++-Build</em>:</li>
  <li>Disable <em>Generate Makefiles automatically</em></li>
  <li>Disable <em>Use default build command</em></li>
  <li>Choose <em>Build directory: ...</em> -> Click <em>Filesystem</em> -> 
    Choose newly created folder <tt>build_debug</tt>
  </li>
  <li>In <em>Behaviour</em>: In <em>Build (incremential build)</em> remove 
    <em>all</em>
  </li>
  <li>Disable automatically build: In Heading bar: <em>Project</em> -> remove 
    <em>Build automatically</em>
  </li>
</ol>

You find the binary in <tt>ug4/bin/</tt> with the name <tt>ugshell</tt>


<hr>
\section secInstallEcpliseRunExecutable Run ug-executable via Eclipse

If you want you can also start the executable from <em>Eclipse</em>.
This is especially useful if you like to use the build-in Debugger. 

<ol>
  <li><tt>ug4</tt> -> <em>Properties</em></li>
  <li><em>Run/Debug Settings</em></li>
  <li>Click <em>New ...</em> -> <em>C/C++ Application</em></li>
  <li>Fill in executable: <em>Browse</em> -> <tt>ug4/bin/ugshell</tt></li>
  <li>Choose <em>Arguments</em> -> <em>Program arguments</em>: Fill in: 
    <tt>-ex laplace.lua</tt>
  </li>
</ol>

Of course, if needed, use adapted arguments.


