\section secInstallEcplisePathSymbols Path and Symbols

<em>Eclipse</em> has a powerful Autocompletion-Mechanism, Syntax-Highlighting 
for C++ and many other things.
To make them available, you have to tell <em>Eclipse</em>, where to look for:

<ol>
  <li>Click right on folder <tt>ug4</tt> -> Choose <em>Properties</em></li>
  <li>Under <em>C/C++-General</em> -> <em>Path and Symbols</em></li>
  <li>Under <em>Includes</em> click <em>Add ...</em></li>
  <li>Click on <em>Workspace ...</em> and choose the folder <tt>ugbase</tt></li>
  <li>Check: <em>Add to all languages</em> and <em>Add to all configurations</em></li>
</ol> 

If you use build flags, you must tell <em>Eclipse</em> to recognize them.
Specially, if you do not use <tt>UG_PARALLEL</tt>, all parallel code will not 
be highlighted but regarded as dead code.
So, add it to the Environment:

<ol>
  <li>Click right on folder <tt>ug4</tt> -> Choose <em>Properties</em></li>
  <li>Under <em>C/C++-General</em> -> <em>Path and Symbols</em></li>
  <li>Under <em>Symbols</em> click <em>Add ...</em></li>
  <li>Fill in <tt>UG_PARALLEL</tt>, value: <tt>ON</tt></li>
  <li>Check: <em>Add to all languages</em> and <em>Add to all configurations</em></li>
</ol> 


